theme_set(theme_minimal())

Baboon Activities

We’re going to explore some real baboon activity data collected during the year 2000 from 64 adult female baboons in 5 social groups in the Amboseli basin, Kenya.

We first use the read_csv() function from the readr package. Before executing this code, you must download the data file and place it in a sub-folder called “data” located in your working directory. It might need to be modified, depending on what your folder is called.

# Read baboon activity data
b_acts <- read_csv("04_viz-amounts/data/baboon_acts_2000.csv")

First, an annoyance to fix. The column “month_of” was interpreted as a character string. By default, it will be sorted alphabetically, but we want the months in their natural order. The following line reorders the months using a built-in set of month abbreviations called month.abb.

b_acts$month_of <- factor(b_acts$month_of, levels = month.abb)

Let’s look at the first 10 rows of data in a table using the kable function that you saw last week. We’ll use the head() function to get 10 rows.

More Pies

Let’s build on our previous activity by making a pie chart out of this data (using the column activity). In addition, let’s use a scale_ function to map activity to a color scheme that is slightly less retina-scorching. In particular: scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set1") uses a colorbrewer color palette called “Set1” for the fill aesthetic. These come with ggplot2. I also suggest using theme_void(), and setting color = "white" in geom_bar() so that the wedges are more clearly separable.

ggplot(b_acts, aes(x = "", fill = activity)) +
  geom_bar(position = "fill", color = "white") +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set1") +
  coord_polar(theta = "y") +
  theme_void()

This will be our starting point for pies.



Small Multiples

Let’s re-plot the baboon activity data in pies, this time separately by month. All we need to do is tack on a facet_wrap() line and provide it with the variable by which we want to break the data apart (after a ~ symbol, which in many tidyverse functions stands for “as a function of”).

Specifically, facet the plot by the variable month_of.

Small multiple pies, collapsed

These monstrocities still have way too many categories to be useful. The normal pie chart can be made (marginally) acceptable by displaying only two categories. To do this, we need to collapse all but one category into a new category called “Other”. Let’s compare the proportion of time spent walking to all other categories in each month.

The collapsing can be done easily using the tidyverse package forcats. Yes, that is the actual name. It is used for categorical data. Get it?!!?! Ehh… anyway, all forcats functions start with the prefix fct_. Here, fct_other() is exactly what we need. See if you can figure out how to use it by reading the help file.

Hint: use it when the variable activity appears in the code: fct_other(activity, <stuff here>).

Note that the legend title becomes unruly by calling fct_other() function within the aes() function. You can fix this by entering a legend title manually in the scale_ function: scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set1", name = "activity").

Bar Charts

Leaving behind the world of pies, we now turn our attention to bar charts.

Bad stacked bar

This is our basic starting point for bars: NOT IDEAL

ggplot(b_acts, aes(x = month_of, fill = activity)) +
  geom_bar(color = "white") +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set1", direction = -1) + # Flip direction because I like having red on the bottom
  labs(x = "Month", y = "Number of Samples")

Ordered stacked bar

We can improve this slightly by reordering the activities in order of their frequencies. For this, we can use another forcats function fct_reorder(), which as the name suggests reorders the category by some other variable. We first need to create the variable by which to order. Specifically, we want to count the number of rows with of each activity. dplyr has a convenient function called add_count() for this purpose.

As for the reordering, to avoid having to do it in every single plot, we’ll just do it once on the original data set.

I’ll provide this code:

# How to use: add_count(<name of data>, <name of variable to count>)
# The count is added in a new column called "n"
# You'll learn more about the %>% symbol and the mutate() function later.
b_acts <- add_count(b_acts, activity) %>% 
  mutate(activity = fct_reorder(activity, n))

# Now use our code from the starting point to make another bar chart, but this time use fct_reorder like you used fct_other above.
# your R code goes here

Still, It’s hard to make meaningful comparisons across months for two main reasons:

  1. The categories start and end at different baselines, which makes them hard to compare. For example, were there more total Walk (blue) samples in February or September?
  2. The different months have different total sample sizes, which makes the relative frequencies hard to interpret. For example, is Rest (green) a larger part of the activity budget in January, June, September, or November? Who knows.

Our main interest here is the activity budget, which is measured in proportions rather than raw counts. What proportion of time did the baboons spend resting, feeding, socializing, etc.?

Some of the “better alternative” plots that we will try to produce require that we summarize the data by actually calculating the proportions. As you will see, we can easily recreate the bar charts that we have already made from the summarized data using geom_col(), for which the default stat is "identity" rather than "count".

Here’s a bit of dplyr magic that may look cryptic now but, by the end of this course, you will be able to understand it. This produces our summarized data set:

b_acts_prop <- b_acts %>% 
  group_by(month_of) %>% 
  count(activity) %>% 
  mutate(prop = nn / sum(nn)) %>% 
  ungroup() %>%
  complete(month_of, activity, fill = list(prop = 0, nn = 0))

kable(head(b_acts_prop, n = 10))

Verify that we get the same stacked plots with geom_bar() and geom_col()

# First plot using geom_bar() and original data
p1 <-   ggplot(b_acts, aes(x = month_of, fill = activity)) +
  geom_bar(color = "white") +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set1", direction = -1) +
  labs(x = "Month", y = "Number of Samples", title = "Using geom_bar()")

# Second plot using geom_col() and summarized data (b_acts_prop)
p2 <- ggplot(b_acts_prop, aes(x = month_of, y = nn, fill = activity)) +
  geom_col(color = "white") +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set1", direction = -1) +
  labs(x = "Month", y = "Number of Samples", title = "Using geom_col()")

plot_grid(p1, p2, nrow = 2)

One of the suggestions in the article is simply to include less data in the plot. For example, if all we want to visualize is a trade-off between feeding and resting, then all the other categories are just a distraction from the main message. We can obtain subsets of data by using the dplyr function filter().

We will explore filter() in more detail later in the course, but here’s the template:

filter(<data>, <conditions on which to filter>)

The conditions have to be logical—that is, they must evaluate to TRUE or FALSE. We test, one at a time, whether activity is equal to “Feed” OR whether activity is equal to “Rest”. In R, the symbol | means “or”. If either condition is true (condition1 | condition2), then the row is retained in the filtered data subset.

Plot Feed and Rest in line chart

feed_rest <- filter(b_acts_prop, activity == "Feed" | activity == "Rest")

Filled bars with feeding highlighted and others in varying shades of gray

This one is tricky, so I’ll provide the code. See if you can work out what fct_relevel() is doing by reading the help, and how I created the custom grays + blue color scheme using scale_fill_manual().

grays <- gray.colors(7, start = 0.9, end = 0.5)
ggplot(b_acts_prop, aes(x = month_of, y = prop, fill = fct_relevel(activity, "Feed", after = Inf))) +
  geom_col(color = "white") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c(grays, "lightblue"), name = "activity") +
  labs(x = "Month", y = "Proportion of Samples")

Only distinguish Feed

One way to accomplish this is by plotting two sets of bars:

  • First, the original set of all activities, but all have the same gray fill (and no color)
  • A filtered subset of Feed data only on top of the other bars with fill set to light blue

A few extras

Finally, let’s make two more plots shown in Chapter 6 of Wilke’s Data Visualization: dot plots and a heat map.

Bad birth plot using bars

Here, we want to plot the birth dates of all distinct baboon in the data set. We can get all distinct combinations of baboons and birth dates (the variables sname and birth, respectively) using the dplyr function distinct(). The template is similar to other dplyr functions that you have seen:

distinct(<data>, <variables separated by commas>)

distinct_baboons <- distinct(b_acts, sname, birth)

ggplot(distinct_baboons, aes(x = sname, y = birth)) +
  geom_col() +
  labs(x = "Baboon ID", y = "Year of Birth")

Wow, what a mess. This is a terrible use of a bar chart. The common baseline, which starts at 1970, is completelty meaningless. The youngest animals have the longest bars! The x-axis labels are all squished together. Also, it would be easier to understand the plot if the baboons were in order of birth.

Make this easier to read by using points rather than bars, flipping the x and y axis, and reordering the baboons by date of birth (hint: fct_reorder the category sname by the variable birth).

Heatmap

Finally, let’s make a heat map. As you saw in the chapter, heatmaps map amounts onto colors rather than x and y positions. They’re made by mapping one category to x, another category to y, and a numeric amount to fill. Then, the tiles are made by using the geom_tile() function.

Here’s a really basic version:

ggplot(b_acts_prop, aes(x = month_of, y = activity, fill = prop)) +
geom_tile()

Some tips to improve appearance:

  • In geom_tile(), set color = "white", size = 0.5 to give the tiles thin white borders.
  • You can force the tiles to be perfect squares by using coord_equal()
  • A nice continuous color gradient is scale_fill_viridis_c(). Try the various options (magma, inferno, plasma, viridis, and cividis)! For example, scale_fill_viridis_c(option = "inferno").
